  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering. These laws and frameworks are established through various international organizations and agreements to ensure cooperation among countries in preventing and addressing money laundering activities. Here are some key components:\n\n### 1. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Also known as the Vienna Convention, it was the first international treaty to criminalize money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: This convention addresses corruption and includes measures to prevent and combat money laundering.\n\n### 2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   The **FATF** is an intergovernmental organization established in 1989 to develop policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. It sets international standards known as the **FATF Recommendations**, which provide a comprehensive framework for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) efforts. These recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n### 3. **European Union Directives**\n   The **European Union (EU)** has implemented several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs) to harmonize AML measures across member states. The latest directive, **AMLD6**, strengthens previous measures and introduces stricter requirements for transparency and due diligence.\n\n### 4. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**\n   The IMF and World Bank support anti-money laundering efforts through technical assistance, assessments, and monitoring of compliance with international AML standards.\n\n### 5. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   The Basel Committee provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering, including recommendations on customer due diligence and suspicious transaction reporting.\n\n### 6. **Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units**\n   This group facilitates international cooperation among financial intelligence units (FIUs) to combat money laundering and terrorist financing by sharing information and best practices.\n\n### 7. **Bilateral and Multilateral Agreements**\n   Many countries have entered into bilateral or multilateral agreements to enhance cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases.\n\n### Key Requirements of International AML Frameworks\n- **Criminalization of Money Laundering**: Making money laundering a criminal offense.\n- **Customer Due Diligence (CDD)**: Financial institutions must verify the identity of their customers and assess the risks associated with their transactions.\n- **Reporting Suspicious Activities**: Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions to financial intelligence units.\n- **Record-Keeping**: Maintaining records of financial transactions for a specified period.\n- **International Cooperation**: Sharing information and coordinating efforts across jurisdictions.\n\nWhile these international frameworks provide a foundation, individual countries implement their own laws and regulations to comply with these standards and address specific risks within their jurisdictions.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
